[2]
Date: Thu, 04 Sep 1997 08:23:31 -0700
From: "Paul D. Millikin" <millikin@mtco.com>
Is human Pfiesteriosis another emerging human infection, caused by a
toxin-producing organism? Do the described skin sores represent a
Pfiesterial infection? If so, by what life form of Pfiesteria? Ameboid?
Can Pfiesteria become invasive and cause lesions elsewhere in the body?
Liver, for example, or lungs, or brain? If so, can it produce toxin in
those locations?
As precedents, quite a few other organisms can cause skin sores, Buruli
ulcer, for example. Amebae can become invasive, producing liver abscesses
and meningitis. And humans are heirs to quite a few toxin-producing
organisms such as Corynebacterium diphtheriae and assorted Clostridia.
Does ANYBODY know the answers to those questions, or is ANYBODY working on
them? It's about time we got a handle on the human side of this little
beastie.
--
Paul D. Millikin, MD
Dep't of Pathology
UICOMP (University of Illinois College of Medicine at Peoria)
Peoria, IL
